INTRODUCTION

IN this brief introduction an attempt will be made to give an outline of the general tendencies of Latin literature. The subject merits some attention, inso- much as the emphasis constantly laid upon the Greek origin of Roman literary forms has tended to obscure the fact that the strongest forces in Latin literature were not due to Greek or any other influence, but were J its own, its peculiar birthright. They were qualities derived from certain inherent characteristics of the Roman people, which showed themselves in the very earliest monuments of their literature, and which per- sisted throughout its history in spite of much run- ning after foreign models and, in more than one period, of an unfavorable social or political omilim.
